about Professor Altman.

00:02:08.950 --> 00:02:11.220
Sidney Altman is internationally renowned

00:02:11.220 --> 00:02:12.760
for his important contributions

00:02:12.760 --> 00:02:15.763
to the fields of biochemistry
and molecular biology.

00:02:16.640 --> 00:02:21.080
He and Thomas Cech share the
1989 Nobel Prize in chemistry

00:02:21.080 --> 00:02:22.320
for their independent studies

00:02:22.320 --> 00:02:26.313
demonstrating the
catalytic ability of RNA.

00:02:27.290 --> 00:02:30.762
Altman discovered RNase P
and the enzymatic properties

00:02:30.762 --> 00:02:34.220
of the RNA subunit of that enzyme.

00:02:34.220 --> 00:02:37.340
He found that RNA, which
was previously believed

00:02:37.340 --> 00:02:40.720
to be simply a passive
carrier of genetic codes

00:02:40.720 --> 00:02:43.010
between different parts of the cell,

00:02:43.010 --> 00:02:46.520
could also initiate
and catalyze reactions.

00:02:46.520 --> 00:02:50.390
This discovery refuted the
formerly unquestioned principle

00:02:50.390 --> 00:02:54.310
that molecules could either
carry information like RNA

00:02:54.310 --> 00:02:57.950
or catalyze chemical
reactions like proteins,

00:02:57.950 --> 00:02:59.980
but they could not do both.

00:02:59.980 --> 00:03:02.370
I apologize for the music.

00:03:02.370 --> 00:03:05.430
Altman's breakthrough opened
up many new fields of research

00:03:05.430 --> 00:03:09.210
and biotechnology, especially
focused on RNA structure

00:03:09.210 --> 00:03:10.083
and function.

00:03:11.340 --> 00:03:13.020
Professor Altman has been a faculty member

00:03:13.020 --> 00:03:15.490
at Yale University since 1971,

00:03:15.490 --> 00:03:19.050
teaching both undergraduate
and graduate courses.

00:03:19.050 --> 00:03:21.180
Also at Yale, he has served as a chair

00:03:21.180 --> 00:03:25.510
of the department of biology, 1983 to '85,

00:03:25.510 --> 00:03:29.170
and dean of Yale College, 1985 to '89,

00:03:29.170 --> 00:03:31.940
and is currently the Sterling Professor

00:03:31.940 --> 00:03:35.930
of Molecular, Cellular,
and Developmental Biology.

00:03:35.930 --> 00:03:38.770
Since his Nobel Prize in 1989,

00:03:38.770 --> 00:03:40.850
he has been awarded honorary degrees

00:03:40.850 --> 00:03:43.590
from the University of
Montreal, New York University,

00:03:43.590 --> 00:03:45.799
Connecticut College, McGill University,

00:03:45.799 --> 00:03:50.200
University of Colorado,
University of British Columbia,

00:03:50.200 --> 00:03:52.830
Dartmouth College, Lake Forest College,

00:03:52.830 --> 00:03:55.903
Concordia University, and
the University of Toronto.

00:03:56.790 --> 00:03:59.600
In recognition of his
illuminating research,

00:03:59.600 --> 00:04:00.870
Altman has been named a fellow

00:04:00.870 --> 00:04:02.810
by the University of Colorado,

00:04:02.810 --> 00:04:05.980
the Damon Runyon Fund,
the Anna Fuller Fund,

00:04:05.980 --> 00:04:08.210
the California Institute of Technology,

00:04:08.210 --> 00:04:10.210
and Dartmouth College.

00:04:10.210 --> 00:04:12.570
Altman currently serves on
the Committee on Human Rights

00:04:12.570 --> 00:04:14.920
of the National Academy of Sciences.

00:04:14.920 --> 00:04:17.560
He has been on the board of trustees

00:04:17.560 --> 00:04:18.540
of the Dime Institute

00:04:18.540 --> 00:04:21.230
for the History of Science and Technology.

00:04:21.230 --> 00:04:22.940
He has received a Rosentee Award

00:04:22.940 --> 00:04:26.310
for basic biomedical research,
and that was in 1989.

00:04:27.710 --> 00:04:29.983
Innovators of Science Award, 1992,

00:04:31.540 --> 00:04:36.170
the Novartis Drew Award in
biomedical research in 1999,

00:04:36.170 --> 00:04:37.810
and is an Einstein professor

00:04:37.810 --> 00:04:40.090
of the Chinese Academy of Sciences

00:04:40.090 --> 00:04:41.620
as well as a visiting professor

00:04:41.620 --> 00:04:43.790
at the University of Glasgow.

